query_1.text: Jeanne d'Arc, also known as Joan of Arc, was a French heroine and military leader who played a significant role in the Hundred Years' War. She claimed to have received visions from saints instructing her to support Charles VII and help him claim the French throne. Jeanne led the French army to several key victories, most notably the lifting of the siege of Orléans. She was later captured by the English, tried for heresy, and burned at the stake. Jeanne d'Arc was later canonized as a saint by the Catholic Church.

query_2.text: Jeanne d'Arc was known as the "Maid of Orléans" because of her pivotal role in the siege of Orléans during the Hundred Years' War, where she led the French army to victory against the English in 1429.

query_3.text: Jeanne d'Arc led the French army in the Hundred Years' War from 1429 to 1430.

query_4.text: Jeanne d'Arc experienced her visions and received her divine guidance in the village of Domrémy, France.

query_5.text: Jeanne d'Arc was ultimately captured and tried for heresy because she claimed to have received divine guidance from God, which was seen as a challenge to the authority of the church during that time.

query_6.text: Jeanne d'Arc inspired and influenced the French army during her military campaigns by boosting morale, providing strategic guidance, and leading with courage and determination.
